<TEXT>
dozens of prominent leftists are 
returning from exile to join the campaign against military 
president augusto pinochet but some are bringing embarrassment as 
well as enthusiasm to the opposition 
police said wednesday that 53 of the 504 leftists affected by 
pinochets sept 1 decision to end all official exile have returned 
home 
the list includes prominent members of the leftist government of 
president salvador allende ousted by pinochet in a bloody 1973 
coup and leaders of marxist parties that supported it 
most of the returning exiles have declared support for an 
opposition campaign to defeat pinochet in an oct 5 presidential 
referendum but some are also making radical statements that 
conflict with the oppositions campaign strategy 
in the referendum 74 million registered voters will vote on a 
proposal by the countrys military commanders that pinochet remain 
in power until 1997 
if a majority vote yes pinochet will start a new eightyear 
term next march 11 if the no vote prevails an open election will 
be called next year and pinochet will hand over power to the winner 
in 1990 
a 16party coalition is busily campaigning for pinochets defeat 
images of joyful dissidents returning to their homeland after 
more than a decade in exile have provided an emotional charge to 
campaign 
a huge airport crowd is expected saturday for the scheduled 
arrival of allendes widow hortensia bussi 
allende died in the takeover and his wife fled the country days 
later emerging as a major critic of pinochet her visit is 
expected to give the opposition a major boost 
but some of the exiles appear too outspoken for the moderate 
oppositions tastes 
volodia teitelboim a former senator and a leader of the 
proscribed communist party returned on tuesday from exile in 
moscow and promptly criticized the opposition strategy 
he said it lacks real unity because the communists are 
excluded from the coalition whose members range from the 
centerright to socialist left 
he also criticized six parties from the right to the centerleft 
for joining in a coalition to form a moderate transition government 
in case pinochet loses 
the new coalition announced wednesday and led by the moderate 
christian democratic party the nations largest said its goal is 
to offer chileans an alternative of government for the first 
democatic period after pinochet 
the opposition leaders have carefully avoided comment on the 
remarks by teitelboim and others 
patricio aylwin president of the christian democrats asked 
about teitelboims criticism replied only the communist party 
is not a member of our coalition 
genaro arriagada secretarygeneral of the coalition recently 
defended the leftists inalienable right to return to their 
homeland when they chose even if it might not be the best moment 
for their arrival 
we have no moral right to ask that they postpone their 
return he said at a news conference 
progovernment media are enthusiastically selecting and 
broadcasting some statements by the returning exiles to emphasize 
its claim that the opposition is dominated by the extreme left 
when mario palestro a radical socialist excongressman 
returned to chile last week he paid homage to my comrades of 
the leftist revolutionary movement a guerrilla band he warned 
that when the people recover power many rightwingers will 
have to flee the country like rabbits 
since then government political ads on television have 
repeatedly shown palestro making his fierce speech upon arrival at 
the airport 
maria eugenia oyarzun a progovernment political commentator 
said in the newspaper la tercera last sunday that the returning 
exiles are ruining the oppositions efforts to cultivate an image 
of moderation 
defense minister adm patricio carvajal said on wednesday i 
think its very good that these people are returning so chileans 
can see the the continued disorder and split within the 
opposition 
</TEXT>
