a medical student who thought his dream of 
sending a science project into space exploded with the illfated 
challenger mission will get another chance with the launch of the 
space shuttle discovery next thursday 
its good to continue something you believe in said richard 
cavoli whose work was praised by president reagan in his 1986 
state of the union address 
cavoli now a secondyear medical student at the university of 
buffalo said he feared that the challenger disaster would put an 
end to manned space exploration 
i was afraid people would say it wasnt worthwhile he said 
thursday at a news conference in buffalo i think it is a lot of 
problems we have on earth can be solved in space 
cavolis project involves growing crystals under zerogravity 
conditions he theorizes that gravity creates currents in chemical 
solutions that disrupt formation of crystals he said leadiodide 
crystals formed in space might be larger and purer and lead to 
improved film for xrays and improved semiconductors in computers 
cavoli 24 first thought of the experiment as a high school 
student while he attended union college in schenectady school 
officials sponsored the experiment spending more than 14000 
union chemistry professor charles scaife helped cavoli refine 
the experiment and rebuild the equipment destroyed in the explosion 
the project is one of only two student experiments being 
conducted by discovery astronauts other experiments that were part 
of the challenger mission have been cancelled by nasa 
cavoli was in washington watching a broadcast of the challenger 
