<TEXT>
airlines have been ordered to equip their jet 
fleets over the next four years with devices to help pilots escape 
deadly wind shears that have been linked to five major accidents 
and more than 500 deaths in the last decade 
the federal aviation administration announced the new 
requirements on thursday they call for a phasein of the wind 
shear detection equipment on more than 3600 jetliners by late 1992 
powerful shears called microbursts have been called the no 1 
killer of airline passengers and have been responsible for 18 
airline accidents and 575 deaths since 1970 
the faa regulation was announced by the transportation 
department and covers any commercial jetliner with 30 or more 
seats the department estimated the cost to the airlines at between 
40000 ando 50000 per airplane 
a microburst is a powerful downburst of air caused by a sudden 
change in wind direction that can literally drive a jetliner into 
the ground if encountered during an approach or departure 
in 1985 a microburst struck a delta air lines l1011 as it was 
attempting to land at dallasfort worth causing a crash that 
killed 134 people a pan american world airways jet encountered a 
strong shear while trying to take off from the new orleans airport 
in 1982 and crashed killing 154 people 
the delta accident focused increased attention on developing and 
installing sophisticated ground radar that would provide advanced 
warning of shears along departure and approach lanes but the radar 
is not expected to be available until the early 1990s and then only 
at a relatively small number of airports 
at the same time the faa and industry began examining training 
methods to help pilots detect a shear and possibly escape although 
most pilots say there are microbursts that cannot be flown through 
if encountered at a low altitude such as during a takeoff or 
approach 
the technology to help pilots escape a shear has been available 
for several years piedmont airlines two years ago began installing 
the equipment being required by the faa and today has the devices 
in 112 of its 191 aircraft according to piedmont spokesman mike 
clark 
but some airline executives and pilots question the value of the 
devices 
the critics note that the equipment is not a radar and thus 
would only help a pilot recognize when the plane already has flown 
into wind shear conditions by then it may be too late to escape if 
the plane is close to the ground they maintain 
transportation secretary jim burnley in announcing the new 
requirements said the equipment will enhance safety by giving 
pilots a valuable tool for coping with the dangerous wind shear 
phenomenon 
experience has shown that pilots can recover successfully from 
wind shear encounters if they can recognize the situation quickly 
enough and have sufficient information to execute escape 
maneuvers he said in a statement 
the faa regulation says half of an airlines fleet must have the 
devices within 27 months threefourths of the fleet within 39 
months and the rest of the fleet within 51 months 
the rule also requires airlines to provide pilots with increased 
training on wind shear recognition and recovery procedures while 
using the new equipment 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

