states to collect identifying information on people who test 
positive for the aids virus 
opponents successfully argued that anonymous testing is a much 
better way to attract people at highest risk of being infected with 
aids and that testing resources need to be concentrated on those 
people rather than populations that probably havent been exposed 
lets not take limited resources and waste them said 
rep henry waxman dcalif chief sponsor of the testing measure 
let the states do their own efforts as they see fit 
the waxman bill would give states complying with its terms an 
extra 400 million a year to conduct widespread voluntary aids 
testing and counseling 
it also would protect the confidentiality of counseling and 
testing records speed up research into acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome and create a national commission to advise congress on 
issues raised by the fatal disease 
final house action could come as early as today the bill then 
goes to the senate 
the human rights campaign fund a political action committee for 
the gay and lesbian community praised the house for rejecting what 
it called hostile amendments proposed by rep william dannemeyer 
rcalif and other conservatives 
members of the house have sent a clear signal to rep 
dannemeyer and others who support irrational punitive aids actions 
that the time has come for responsible aids policy the funds 
executive director vic basile said in a statement 
the virus that causes aids a fatal disease most often is 
spread through close contact with contaminated blood products or 
semen its principal victims have been homosexuals and intravenous 
drug users 
the house agreed to require testing of prisoners convicted of 
prostitution or crimes related to sexual assault or iv drug abuse 
the plan was approved 266137 as an alternative to mandatory 
testing of all prisoners 
amendments defeated thursday included 
a proposal to require testing of all marriage license 
applicants in states where the incidence of aids infection is over 
one in 1000 sponsored by rep bill mccollum rfla it lost 
30491 
rep edward madigan rill said his states program has 
identified nine applicants infected with aids out of 75000 people 
tested at a cost to newlyweds of 400000 for each identified 
case he said the governor has requested it be repealed 
rep lindy boggs dla said her state repealed its requirement 
after a year because it was an economic hardship produced a 
significant number of false positive tests and did nothing for 
those groups at highest risk lets not force our mistake on the 
rest of the nation she said 
a proposal to require hospitals in highincidence states to 
test virtually all inpatients between ages 15 and 50 sponsored by 
dannemeyer it lost 30289 health workers are expected to treat 
all patients as infected and protect themselves accordingly 
madigan said 
a proposal to require reporting of aidsinfected individuals 
with enough information to locate them another dannemeyer 
initiative it lost 32770 
proponents accused congress of ignoring the need for information 
on the epidemic but opponents said demographic data on 
aidsinfected people must be reported under the bill and 
identifying information would drive people underground 
the lawmakers cited the case of oregon where a switch to 
anonymous testing resulted in a 125 percent increase in the number 
of homosexual men being tested and a 56 percent increase in the 
number of prostitutes tested they also noted that in south 
carolina a switch to name reporting resulted in a 51 percent drop 
in the number of homosexual men being tested at a charleston site 
