a ruling by the nuclear regulation commission 
raises the possibility that the idled seabrook nh reactor may 
never be allowed to operate commercially 
the commission said thursday that before receiving a lowpower 
license the financially troubled seabrook owners must prove they 
can pay for decommissioning the reactor in the event they 
eventually fail to gain a fullpower license 
in a unanimous vote without debate the commissioners ordered 
seabrook to submit a plan within 30 days that provides reasonable 
assurance that adequate funds will be available so that safe 
decommissioning will be reasonably assured 
seabrook officials expressed optimism that they would be able to 
satisfy the commissioners 
were in the process of answering those questions right now 
and were confident this wont be an issue barring us from 
lowpower testing said ronald a sher spokesman for new 
hampshire yankee the plants operator 
some opponents said they too expected the nrc to approve the 
companys decommissioning plan 
its not very hard to satisfy the nrc if youre a nuclear 
utility said robert backus a new hampshire attorney for the 
seacoast antipollution league 
but others said they were cautiously optimistic about the agency 
they regularly criticize for being too soft on the nuclear industry 
massachusetts attorney general james shannon who opposes an 
operating license for seabrook said the ruling was frankly 
unexpected by us and makes us feel that as this goes along theyre 
going to pay closer attention to the finacial stability 
a ruling on the decommissioning question could not come until 
midnovember at the earliest 
seabrook officials said they have no estimate on decommissioning 
costs but said lowpower testing would add about 4 million to the 
cost opponents disputed that figure saying it was much too low 
the commission also has to resolve the separate question of 
whether seabrooks owners are financially fit to operate the plant 
martin malsch the nrc deputy general counsel said the agency 
hopes to settle that matter within a month 
the two financial qualification issues represent the only 
regulatory obstacles remaining in seabrooks prolonged quest for a 
license that would allow the owners to test the reactor at 5 
percent of power lowpower testing is a necessary step to 
obtaining a commercial license to operate the plant at full power 
the license is also pivotal for seabrook opponents they say the 
5 percent testing would contaminate the reactor with radioactive 
fuel making it much more difficult to convert the plant to a 
gasfired facility or to decommission it 
