orders for big ticket durable goods soared 
60 percent in august on the strength of big jumps in the military 
and transportation sectors the government said today 
the commerce department said total orders jumped to a seasonally 
adjusted 1231 billion last month the big jump follows a huge 74 
percent decline in july the biggest in more than four years and 
an 87 percent increase in june which was the largest in 30 months 
orders for transportation equipment in august were up by 209 
percent to 354 billion more than half the increase was for motor 
vehicles and parts auto orders had been weak in july as factories 
were switching over to a new model year 
that follows a 224 percent plunge in july and a 333 percent 
gain in june the transportation category has been buffeted back 
and forth in recent months by big swings in orders for aircraft 
ships and tanks 
orders for defense goods jumped 153 percent in august to 81 
billion following a 494 percent drop in july and a 683 percent 
increase in june this category which is also very volatile from 
month to month overlaps transportation and includes military 
planes tanks and ships 
excluding defense goods orders rose 54 percent last month 
following a decline of 22 percent in july and an increase of 42 
percent in june 
excluding transportation orders rose 10 percent in august 
fell 09 percent in july and rose 07 percent in june 
orders in the key category of nondefense capital goods a good 
barometer of business expansion plans were up 54 percent in 
august to 382 billion following gains of 22 percent in july and 
125 percent in june this has been one of the strongest areas of 
the economy as manufacturers gear up to meet a boom in export sales 
orders for primary metals such as steel fell 16 percent in 
august following small declines in july and june 
orders for the machinery category which includes computers rose 
42 percent in august after falling 29 percent a month earlier 
other kinds of electrical machinery were off 04 percent after a 
32 percent gain in july 
shipments of durable goods rose 44 percent in august to 1182 
billion following a 29 percent drop in july 
