<TEXT>
doctors who go short on sleep because of their 
rigorous hospital schedules can care for patients just as well as 
doctors who are wellrested according to a new study 
the report in fridays editions of the journal of the american 
medical association disputes other studies showing that prolonged 
sleep loss adversely affects mental functions said dr timothy f 
deaconson its chief author 
we conclude that the repetitive episodes of sleep deprivation 
associated with an everyothernight oncall schedule do not impair 
the performance of residents the study found 
sleep deprivation was defined as a lack of four continuous hours 
of sleep during the preceding 24hour period the study said 
that condition occurred in 89 percent of 20 nights covered by 
the study among the 26 residents at milwaukee county hospital 
researchers at the medical college of wisconsin in milwaukee 
led by deaconson investigated whether surgical residents 
performance was hurt by their sleep loss due to schedules that 
require them to work all night 
the residents kept diaries detailing the amount of sleep they 
received and then were tested for rapid handeye coordination 
visual and auditory skills and understanding 
i was not surprised at the results deaconson said in an 
interview thursday i was surprised at how onesided they were i 
was surprised there was very little difference between the sleep 
deprived residents and those who got rest 
i was expecting some people to show a difference and some not 
to and i was surprised that the results were so uniform he said 
the study comes as hospitals and doctors are looking into the 
possibility of reducing the number of hours residents are forced to 
work because of concerns for patient care 
deaconsons study said the issue should not be decided quickly 
criticism of traditional hospital oncall schedules should be 
based on objective data the study said the evidence available 
to date does not support abitrary recommendations to limit the 
working hours of residents 
