<TEXT>
a group of brokerage firms and an industry 
association are going to court to try to block a new state 
regulation that would guarantee investors the right to sue their 
stockbrokers 
nine major brokerage houses and the securities industry 
association filed the federal lawsuit thursday contending the 
regulation is unconstitutional 
if the federal government were going to do this it might be 
unwise and unnecessary but for states to do it its also 
unconstitutional said gerald f rath an attorney for the 
plaintiffs 
the regulation would forbid stockbrokers from asking their 
clients to sign agreements to submit all disputes to binding 
arbitration many brokerage firms alarmed by a rash of lawsuits 
after the october 19 1987 stock market crash have began 
requesting such agreements from all new clients 
massachusetts is the first state to propose a regulation against 
the practice but 16 other states reportedly may adopt similar 
rules a us house subcommittee also is considering legislation 
that would bar brokerage houses from requiring customers to sign 
arbitration agreements before opening accounts 
if upheld by the courts the massachusetts regulation will take 
effect jan 1 1989 
state officials who unveiled the regulation thursday in 
washington said they anticipated the legal challenge 
were very confident that we are on firm constitutional 
ground said deputy secretary of state martin t meehan weve 
been working with the attorney generals office for months and we 
expect to win in court 
meehan said the antiarbitration guidelines were intended to 
give investors the option of suing brokers in the event of a 
dispute and were drafted because state officials received hundreds 
of complaints from investors after the october crash 
most brokerage firms require customers to settle disputes 
through an arbitration hearing sponsored by the new york stock 
exchange the national association of securities dealers or other 
market organizations 
arbitration generally is cheaper and faster than suing but 
investors have only a limited right to appeal while big 
institutional investors can negotiate contracts with brokerages 
individual investors usually have little choice but to agree to 
arbitration 
the lawsuit asks for an injunction against the regulation and 
names secretary of state michael connolly and state securities 
division director barry c guthary as defendants 
the suit contends arbitration agreements are consistent with the 
1934 securities and exchange act and that the 1925 federal 
arbitration act took away from states the power to pass legislation 
governing such agreements 
under the new regulation stockbrokers could have have their 
licenses suspended or revoked if they refused to accept an 
investors business without an arbitration agreement 
by doing that the suit claims the massachusetts 
antiarbitration regulations purport to place arbitration 
agreements on a different footing from other agreements 
meehan the deputy secretary of state disagreed were not 
claiming that the contract is illegal he said were also not 
claiming to have the authority to get into the reform of 
arbitration mechanics but we clearly have the right to give 
investors the choice as to whether or not they are forced to enter 
into these agreements 
the nine brokerage houses that filed the suit are 
dean witter reynolds inc donaldson lufkin amp jenrette 
securities corp drexel burnham lambert inc fidelity brokerage 
services inc kidder peabody co merrill lynch pierce fenner 
amp smith inc painewebber inc prudentialbache securities inc 
shearson lehman hutton inc and smith barney harris upham amp co 
a securities and exchange commission survey this year of 65 
firms handling 90 percent of all customer accounts found virtually 
all require arbitration particularly for customers who borrow 
money from the firm through margin accounts or trade in risky stock 
options 
but the securities industry assocation said that since 1981 the 
sec has received more than 156000 complaints by private investors 
against brokers and only 147 involved arbitration 
</TEXT>
